Model 1 - Linear Regression: Which attributes are most influential in predicting the price of a specific product?

To answer fully this question, we decided to separate the main question into 3 subsets questions: - (1) Which product’s attributes will affect the price ? - (2) Which website’s attributes will affect the price ? - (3) Who and when will affect the price ?

After we are able to answer all these 3 subsets questions, we will combine all the attributes and features from the products, website & customers to see how they together affect the price. Also, with 4 models are built, it will be easier for us to compare them, and give better conclusion about which one will be more accuracy & will affect the price more, products, website, customers & time or all of them together.

With the results above, we can conclude:

  • Hypothesis test for whether all independent variables’ coefficient in the model equal to 0 or not - Ho: B1 + B2 + …+ Bk = 0. We see the F-statistic has p-value < 2.2e - 16, we can reject Ho, which means at least one independent variable has some effect on price (Or all independent variables’ coefficient together do not equal to 0).
  • Hypothesis test for whether each independent variable’s coefficient in the model equals to 0 or not - Ho: Bk = 0. We see in the “Pr>(|t|)” column, most of values are <2e-16, we can reject Ho of those values, which means they have significant effect on price - their coefficients do not equal to 0. Except Colour_7, its value is 0.152 > 0.05, we cannot rejecto Ho, colour_7 may not have any effect on price. But in the confident interval 85%, it still might have some effect. We will process with both model, exclude and not exclude colour_7, to see which one is better in prediction.

The rule of thumb is that a regressor produces collinearity if its VIF is greater than 10 . All our regressors have VIF coefficient less than 10, so there is no multicollinearity between each independent variables!

Heteroscedasticity (breusch pagan test - bptest)

As result above for “breusch pagan test”, p-Value < 0.05 indicates that the null hypothesis(the variance is unchanging in the residual) cannot be rejected and therefore heterscedasticity doesn’t exist.

The rule of thumb is that a regressor produces collinearity if its VIF is greater than 10 . All our regressors have VIF coefficient less than 10, so there is no multicollinearity between each independent variables!

Heteroscedasticity (breusch pagan test - bptest)

bptest(mod2)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  mod2
## BP = 4942.5, df = 8, p-value < 2.2e-16

As result above for “breusch pagan test”, p-Value < 0.05 indicates that the null hypothesis(the variance is unchanging in the residual) cannot be rejected and therefore heterscedasticity doesn’t exist.

With the results above, we can conclude:

  • Hypothesis test for whether all independent variables’ coefficient in the model equal to 0 or not - Ho: B1 + B2 + …+ Bk = 0. We see the F-statistic has p-value < 2.2e - 16, we can reject Ho, which means at least one independent variable has some effect on price (Or all independent variables’ coefficient together do not equal to 0).
  • Hypothesis test for whether each independent variable’s coefficient in the model equals to 0 or not - Ho: Bk = 0. We see in the “Pr>(|t|)” column, most of values are <2e-16 <0.05, we can reject Ho of those values, which means they have significant effect on price - their coefficients do not equal to 0 and they are significant at confident interval 95%; Month_7 have p-value <0.1, their coefficient are still significant at confident interval 90%. Others: continent_Oceania & weekday have p-values are very high, we might consider to exclude them out of the model.

Creating a Gains chart and Decile-wise chart

gain <- gains(t1.valid.df$price2, t1.logit.reg.pred, groups=10)

plot(c(0,gain$cume.pct.of.total*sum(t1.valid.df$price2))~c(0,gain$cume.obs),
xlab="# cases", ylab="Cumulative", main="", type="l")
lines(c(0,sum(t1.valid.df$price2))~c(0, dim(t1.valid.df)[1]), lty=2)

# compute deciles and plot decile-wise chart
heights <- gain$mean.resp/mean( t1.valid.df$price2)
midpoints <- barplot(heights, names.arg = gain$depth, ylim = c(0, 2),
                     xlab = "Percentile", ylab = "Mean Response", main = "Decile-wise lift chart")
# add labels to columns
text(midpoints, heights+0.5, labels=round(heights, 1), cex = 0.8)
